{
  "doc_id": "2714",
  "text": "Active tactile sensing is a widespread strategy for near-range orientation in the animal kingdom. The whiskers of mammals [CITATION_1] or antennae of insects and crustacea [CITATION_2] are moved actively to acquire information about the near-range environment. Tactually elicited changes in behaviour often involve fast, adaptive motor reactions. In insects, these adaptive movements include rapid body axis inclination [CITATION_3] or turning [CITATION_4] , but also aimed reaching movements of the front legs [CITATION_5] . These behaviours have in common that tactile information must be mediated to thoracic locomotor networks with short latency.",
